    <text>
        <body>
            <p rend="indent(11)">
                <date>Friday</date>
            </p>
            <p>“Why did <persName>Moses</persName> delay going down from the mountain”? Why has
                there<lb/> been no answer? You have received a fine piece of work. I beg of you<lb/>
                to accept at once both the German as well as the postscript, and also<lb/> to
                translate in to English. Include it in the following number. In<lb/> the postscript
                against <persName>Szold</persName> and <persName>Einhorn</persName>, I want to swat
                two flies at<lb/> once. <sic>Isay</sic> that when one man is a rascal it does not
                mean that the <lb/> other is too. About <persName>Szold</persName> we do not know at
                all what he hold to.<lb/>
                <persName>Einhorn</persName>, at least, said definitely what he wants. For this he
                de-<lb/>serves thanks. “And thou shalt make a fence around thy roof”. Nothing<lb/>
                in this postscript should seem unnatural to him. “The wise man has<lb/> his eyes in
                his head”. But I must urgently request that you send me<lb/> the proof sheets. I
                shall return them to you at once, and there will<lb/> be no delay. The articles are
                very important for our interests.<lb/> That you will discover upon mature
                consideration. Only such language<lb/> is effective. I therefore ask you to print
                the entire sermon and the<lb/> postscript in one issue. You will be able to sell
                separate numbers<lb/> of it. That is why a quarter of a sheet more will not be
                injurious<lb/> Set up the galley and prepare an English translation of the
                sermon.<lb/> Send me at lease ten copies of this issue. <persName>Szold's</persName>
                defense of the<lb/>
                <hi rend="underline">Minhag <placeName>America</placeName></hi> is shameful and is
                completely contrary to <persName>Wise</persName>. As<lb/> I point out in the notes
                    <del>?</del> in calm language, one must stroke<lb/> playfully without
                scratching. “This is the manner of <sic>theTorah</sic>”
                    <persName>Ein-<lb/>horn</persName> does you much honor. He calls you the old
                lion. It is good<lb/> that you can roar while he can only shout. Do no write against
                it.<lb/> “I shall answer my traducers”.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)"><persName>Berend</persName> is crazy. Don't accept anything
                    <sic>fromhim</sic>. He puts<lb/>
                <persName>Jesus</persName> on an equal plane with <persName>Moses</persName>. He is
                an ignoramus and in the<lb/> highest degree confused. At his <date>Sunday</date>
                services, there was “no man<lb/> and no response”. I must end because of the
                approach of the <date>Sabbath</date>.</p>
            <pb n="2"/>
            <p rend="indent(7)">Your friend who respects you with a</p>
            <p rend="indent(8)">sincere heart, which</p>
            <p rend="indent(8)">wails like a dove.</p>
            <p>All the remarks on <sic>themargin</sic> of the pages belong to the text, except<lb/>
                where the word <hi rend="underline">note</hi> is written nearby. That belongs below
                the text.<lb/> There are only two notes- one in the sermon itself and one in
                the<lb/> postscript. I urgently ask you to take the greatest care in the<lb/>
                setting up.</p>
        </body>
